USD::adp employment change weekly::none.note: ADP's weekly NER pulse provides a week-over-week read on US private-sector employment using anonymized payroll data. A stronger pulse can firm USD and often weighs on XAUUSD via higher yields; a softer pulse can support it.

USD::adp nonfarm employment change::none.note: The ADP National Employment Report estimates the monthly change in US private-sector employment using aggregated, anonymized payroll data. Big surprises can move yields and USD and often push XAUUSD the other way.

USD::all car sales::none.note: U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA) reports motor vehicle retail sales for domestic and foreign autos.

USD::all truck sales::none.note: U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA) reports motor vehicle retail sales for light weight trucks.

USD::api weekly crude oil stock::none.note: API's Weekly Statistical Bulletin reports total U.S. and regional crude inventories, alongside refinery operations and other petroleum supply data.

USD::api weekly gasoline stock::none.note: API's Weekly Statistical Bulletin reports inventories of major petroleum products, including motor gasoline.

USD::atlanta fed gdpnow::none.note: Atlanta Fed GDPNow is a nowcasting model that produces a running estimate of US real GDP growth for the current quarter, updating as new data arrive. A stronger nowcast can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; a weaker nowcast can support it.

USD::average hourly earnings (yoy)::y/y.note: Year-over-year growth in BLS Average Hourly Earnings (from the payroll survey) is watched as a wage-inflation signal. Upside surprises can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; downside surprises can be supportive.

USD::average hourly earnings::m/m.note: BLS payroll data (CES) publishes Average Hourly Earnings for employees on private nonfarm payrolls. Faster wage growth can lift yields and USD and often pressures XAUUSD; slower growth can help it.

USD::average weekly hours::none.note: BLS Current Employment Statistics (CES) publishes estimates of average weekly hours for nonfarm payroll employees.

USD::bankruptcy filings::y/y.note: U.S. Courts bankruptcy filing statistics include quarterly bankruptcy filings data tables.

USD::beige book::none.note: The Federal Reserve's Beige Book summarizes anecdotal information on current economic conditions by District and sector.

USD::bloomberg consumer confidence::none.note: Bloomberg Consumer Confidence is a survey-based sentiment reading.

USD::building permits::m/m.note: Census Building Permits Survey provides statistics on the number and valuation of new privately-owned housing units authorized by building permits.

USD::building permits::none.note: Census Building Permits Survey reports the number and valuation of new privately-owned housing units authorized by building permits.

USD::business inventories::m/m.note: Census MTIS report provides monthly measures of combined changes in retail, wholesale, and manufacturing activity, including total business inventories.

USD::cap goods ship non defense ex air::.note: Census M3 survey provides monthly data on manufacturing shipments; this series shows nondefense capital goods shipments excluding aircraft.

USD::capacity utilization rate::none.note: Federal Reserve capacity utilization rate equals an output index divided by a capacity index for manufacturing, mining, and utilities.

USD::cb consumer confidence::none.note: Cb Consumer Confidence is a survey-based sentiment reading.

USD::cb employment trends index::none.note: The Conference Board Employment Trends Index (ETI) is a leading composite index for payroll employment; increases often signal employment growth ahead. A stronger ETI can support USD and often weighs on XAUUSD; a weaker ETI can support it.

USD::cftc wheat speculative net position.note: CFTC COT reports break down each Tuesday's open interest in futures and options; this series shows speculative net positions in wheat.

USD::chain store sales::m/m.note: The ICSC and Goldman Sachs Weekly Chain Store Sales Snapshot measures U.S. nominal comparable-store sales excluding restaurant and vehicle demand.

USD::chain store sales::w/w.note: The ICSC and Goldman Sachs Weekly Chain Store Sales Snapshot measures U.S. nominal comparable-store sales excluding restaurant and vehicle demand.

USD::chain store sales::y/y.note: The ICSC and Goldman Sachs Weekly Chain Store Sales Snapshot measures U.S. nominal comparable-store sales excluding restaurant and vehicle demand.

USD::challenger job cuts::none.note: Challenger, Gray & Christmas reports the number of job cuts announced by U.S.-based employers.

USD::challenger job cuts::y/y.note: Challenger, Gray & Christmas reports the year-over-year change in job cuts announced by U.S.-based employers.

USD::chicago fed national activity::none.note: Chicago Fed National Activity Index (CFNAI) is a monthly index designed to gauge overall economic activity and related inflationary pressure.

USD::chicago fed president evans speaks:.note: Speech by Fed official Chicago FED President Evans.

USD::chicago pmi employment::none.note: ISM-Chicago Business Barometer employment index is a diffusion index based on survey responses from Chicago-area purchasing managers (50 = no change). Stronger readings can lift USD and yields and often pressure XAUUSD; weaker readings can support XAUUSD.

USD::chicago pmi new orders::none.note: ISM-Chicago Business Barometer new orders index is a diffusion index based on survey responses from Chicago-area purchasing managers (50 = no change). Stronger readings can lift USD and yields and often pressure XAUUSD; weaker readings can support XAUUSD.

USD::chicago pmi prices::none.note: ISM-Chicago Business Barometer prices paid index is a diffusion index based on survey responses from Chicago-area purchasing managers (50 = no change). Hotter price signals can lift yields and often pressure XAUUSD; cooler signals can support XAUUSD.

USD::chicago pmi::none.note: ISM-Chicago Business Barometer (Chicago PMI) is a diffusion index based on survey responses from Chicago-area purchasing managers (50 = no change). A higher-than-expected reading can lift USD and yields and often pressure XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support XAUUSD.

USD::cleveland cpi::m/m.note: Cleveland Fed Median CPI is the one-month inflation rate of the CPI component whose expenditure weight sits at the 50th percentile of price changes (based on BLS CPI data). A higher median CPI can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; a lower reading can support it.

USD::construction spending::m/m.note: Census Value of Construction Put in Place Survey provides monthly estimates of the total dollar value of construction work done in the U.S.

USD::consumer credit::none.note: Federal Reserve G.19 reports consumer credit outstanding (revolving and nonrevolving) excluding loans secured by real estate.

USD::continuing jobless claims::none.note: Continuing Jobless Claims is the weekly number of new unemployment benefit claims. Stronger-than-expected labor data (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; weaker data can support it.

USD::core cpi index::none.note: BLS Core CPI (CPI-U less food and energy) index level reflects underlying inflation in prices paid by urban consumers. A firmer core reading can lift real yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; a softer core reading can support it.

USD::core cpi::m/m.note: Month-over-month change in BLS Core CPI (CPI-U less food and energy) is watched as a cleaner read on underlying inflation. Upside surprises can lift yields and often pressure XAUUSD; downside surprises can support it.

USD::core cpi::y/y.note: Year-over-year change in BLS Core CPI (CPI-U less food and energy) reflects the 12-month underlying inflation rate. Hot core inflation can lift USD and yields and often weighs on XAUUSD; cool core inflation can support it.

USD::core durable goods orders::m/m.note: Core Durable Goods Orders measures the month-over-month % change in new orders for long-lasting manufactured goods. A higher-than-expected reading (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support it.

USD::core pce price index::m/m.note: BEA Core PCE price index (PCE excluding food and energy) is released in the Personal Income and Outlays report. As a key Fed inflation gauge, a hotter print can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; a softer print can support it.

USD::core pce price index::y/y.note: Year-over-year change in the BEA Core PCE price index (PCE excluding food and energy) is closely watched for the inflation trend. Upside surprises can lift real yields and often pressure XAUUSD; downside surprises can support it.

USD::core pce prices::none.note: BEA Core PCE price index measures prices paid for goods and services purchased by consumers, excluding food and energy. A higher-than-expected reading can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; a lower reading can support it.

USD::core ppi::m/m.note: BLS Core PPI measures month-over-month changes in selling prices received by domestic producers, excluding food and energy. A hotter reading can lift yields and often pressure XAUUSD; a cooler reading can support it.

USD::core ppi::y/y.note: Year-over-year change in BLS Core PPI reflects producer-level inflation excluding food and energy. Upside surprises can lift USD and yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; downside surprises can support it.

USD::core retail sales::m/m.note: Core Retail Sales measures the month-over-month % change in retail spending. A higher-than-expected reading (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support it.

USD::corporate profits::q/q.note: BEA corporate profits represent the portion of total income earned from current production accounted for by US corporations.

USD::cpi index, n.s.a.::none.note: BLS CPI-U index (not seasonally adjusted) measures the average change over time in prices paid by urban consumers for a market basket of goods and services. A hotter reading can lift yields and often weighs on XAUUSD; a cooler reading can support it.

USD::cpi index, s.a::none.note: Seasonally adjusted CPI-U index level from BLS, designed to remove predictable seasonal patterns in prices. Upside inflation surprises can lift yields and often pressure XAUUSD; downside surprises can support it.

USD::cpi, n.s.a::m/m.note: Month-over-month change in the BLS CPI-U index (not seasonally adjusted), tracking prices paid by urban consumers. A stronger print can lift USD and yields and often weighs on XAUUSD; a weaker print can support it.

USD::cpi::m/m.note: BLS CPI-U month-over-month change measures short-term inflation in prices paid by urban consumers for a market basket. Hot inflation tends to lift yields and weigh on XAUUSD; softer inflation can support it.

USD::cpi::y/y.note: BLS CPI-U year-over-year change reflects the 12-month inflation rate in prices paid by urban consumers. Upside surprises can lift USD/real yields and often pressure XAUUSD; downside surprises can support it.

USD::crude oil imports::none.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report covers U.S. crude oil imports alongside other petroleum supply indicators.

USD::crude oil inventories::none.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report reports U.S. commercial crude oil inventories.

USD::current account::none.note: Current Account reports the current account balance.

USD::cushing crude oil inventories::none.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report includes crude oil inventories at Cushing, Oklahoma.

USD::dallas fed mfg business index::none.note: Dallas Fed Texas Manufacturing Outlook Survey indexes are calculated as the share reporting an increase minus the share reporting a decrease.

USD::dallas fed pce::none.note: Dallas Fed Trimmed Mean PCE inflation rate is an alternative core inflation measure based on BEA PCE price-index data. A higher-than-expected reading can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; a lower reading can support it.

USD::dallas fed services revenues::none.note: Dallas Fed Texas Service Sector Outlook Survey asks firms whether revenue increased, decreased, or was unchanged over the previous month.

USD::discount rate::none.note: Federal Reserve discount window primary credit rate is the interest rate charged on primary credit advances to depository institutions.

USD::distillate fuel production::none.note: EIA reports refinery and blender net production of distillate fuel oil (net production = gross production minus gross inputs).

USD::domestic car sales::none.note: US Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA) reports US sales of domestic autos (vehicles assembled in the US, Canada, and Mexico).

USD::domestic truck sales::none.note: U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA) reports motor vehicle retail sales for domestic light weight trucks.

USD::durable goods orders::m/m.note: Durable Goods Orders measures the month-over-month % change in new orders for long-lasting manufactured goods. A higher-than-expected reading (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support it.

USD::durables excluding defense::m/m.note: Census M3 survey provides monthly statistics on manufacturing activity; this series is durable goods orders excluding defense.

USD::durables excluding transport::m/m.note: Census M3 survey provides monthly statistics on manufacturing activity; this series is durable goods orders excluding transportation.

USD::eia refinery crude runs::w/w.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report includes U.S. crude oil refinery inputs (refinery runs).

USD::eia short - term energy outlook::no.note: EIA Short-Term Energy Outlook provides monthly and yearly energy forecasts and analysis.

USD::eia weekly distillates stocks::none.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report provides weekly estimates of distillate fuel oil inventories.

USD::eia weekly refinery utilization rat.note: EIA refinery utilization rate reflects utilization of atmospheric crude oil distillation units, calculated as gross input divided by last reported operable capacity.

USD::employment benefits::q/q.note: BLS Employment Cost Index measures changes in employers' hourly labor costs; this subseries focuses on benefit costs. Hotter compensation growth can lift yields and often weighs on XAUUSD.

USD::employment cost index::q/q.note: The Employment Cost Index (ECI) measures the change in hourly labor cost to employers over time, including wages and salaries and benefits. Faster-than-expected cost growth can lift yields and often weighs on XAUUSD.

USD::employment wages::q/q.note: BLS Employment Cost Index (wages and salaries) measures changes in employers' hourly wage costs using a fixed labor basket. Faster wage-cost growth can support USD and often pressures XAUUSD via rates.

USD::existing home sales::m/m.note: National Association of Realtors (NAR) Existing-Home Sales covers sales and prices of existing homes (including condos and co-ops) with regional breakdowns.

USD::existing home sales::none.note: National Association of Realtors (NAR) Existing-Home Sales covers sales and prices of existing homes (including condos and co-ops) with regional breakdowns.

USD::export price index::m/m.note: BLS US Export Price Index measures the change over time in prices of goods or services sold to foreign buyers by US residents.

USD::export price index::y/y.note: BLS US Export Price Index measures the change over time in prices of goods or services sold to foreign buyers by US residents.

USD::exports::none.note: BEA defines exports of goods and services as goods and services sold by U.S. residents to foreign residents.

USD::factory orders ex transportation::m.note: Factory Orders excluding transportation removes a volatile category from the Census M3 new-orders data. Strength can support USD and often weighs on XAUUSD; weakness can be supportive.

USD::factory orders::m/m.note: US Census Bureau M3 provides monthly manufacturing shipments, inventories, and new orders (often called Factory Orders). Strong orders can support USD and weigh on XAUUSD; weak orders can support it.

USD::fed bank stress test results::none.note: The Fed's stress test is a forward-looking quantitative evaluation of bank capital under a hypothetical macroeconomic recession scenario.

USD::fed barr testimony::none.note: Testimony by Fed Vice Chair for Supervision Michael Barr, often focused on bank oversight and regulation. A more hawkish policy tone can lift USD and yields and often pressures XAUUSD; a dovish tone can do the opposite.

USD::fed chair powell speaks::none.note: Speech by Fed Chair Jerome Powell.

USD::fed chair powell testifies::none.note: Testimony by Fed Chair Jerome Powell.

USD::fed chair yellen speaks::none.note: Speech by Fed official Janet Yellen.

USD::fed chair yellen testifies::none.note: Testimony by Fed official Janet Yellen.

USD::fed governor jefferson testifies::n.note: Testimony by Fed Governor Philip Jefferson.

USD::fed interest rate decision::none.note: Fed Interest Rate Decision sets the policy rate (the Fed). A more hawkish-than-expected message can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a dovish surprise can support it.

USD::fed labor market conditions index::.note: Kansas City Fed Labor Market Conditions Indicators (LMCI) are two monthly measures based on 24 labor market variables, covering the level and momentum of labor-market activity. Stronger conditions can lift USD and often weigh on XAUUSD; weaker conditions can support it.

USD::fed logan speaks::none.note: Speech by Fed official Lorie Logan.

USD::fed monetary policy report::none.note: The Fed's Monetary Policy Report is the semiannual report to Congress on monetary policy and economic developments.

USD::fed statement::none.note: Fed Statement communicates the policy outlook and guidance (the Fed). A more hawkish-than-expected message can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a dovish surprise can support it.

USD::fed vice chair brainard speaks::non.note: Speech by Fed Vice Chair Lael Brainard.

USD::fed vice chair for supervision barr.note: Speech by Fed Vice Chair for Supervision Michael Barr.

USD::fed waller speaks::none.note: Speech by Fed Governor Christopher Waller.

USD::fed's balance sheet::none.note: The Federal Reserve publishes its balance sheet each week in the H.4.1 statistical release.

USD::federal budget balance::none.note: US Treasury's Monthly Treasury Statement summarizes federal receipts and outlays, producing the monthly budget surplus/deficit. A larger deficit can weigh on USD sentiment at the margin; a smaller deficit can be supportive.

USD::fomc economic projections::none.note: FOMC economic projections (SEP) are collected four times a year and include policymakers' projections for the appropriate target federal funds rate path.

USD::fomc meeting minutes::none.note: FOMC Meeting Minutes provides detail on the latest policy meeting (the Fed). A more hawkish-than-expected message can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a dovish surprise can support it.

USD::fomc member stanley fischer speaks:.note: Speech by Fed official Stanley Fischer.

USD::fomc press conference::none.note: FOMC Press Conference provides Q&A and messaging after the policy decision (the Fed). A more hawkish-than-expected message can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a dovish surprise can support it.

USD::fomc statement::none.note: FOMC Statement communicates the policy outlook and guidance (the Fed). A more hawkish-than-expected message can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a dovish surprise can support it.

USD::gasoline inventories::none.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report includes total motor gasoline inventories.

USD::gasoline production::none.note: EIA reports refinery and blender net production of gasoline (net production = gross production minus gross inputs).

USD::gdp price index::q/q.note: GDP Price Index measures quarter-over-quarter % growth in economic output. A higher-than-expected reading (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support it.

USD::gdp sales::none.note: BEA Final Sales of Domestic Product equals GDP minus the change in private inventories, often read as underlying demand. Stronger final sales can lift yields and often weigh on XAUUSD; weaker final sales can support it.

USD::gdp::q/q.note: GDP measures quarter-over-quarter % growth in economic output. A higher-than-expected reading (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support it.

USD::global semiconductor sales::m/m.note: Semiconductor Industry Association (SIA) reports monthly global semiconductor sales compiled by WSTS (three-month moving average).

USD::gold index::none.note: The Kitco Global Index (KGX) is designed to determine whether changes in gold reflect actual value changes, shifts in the US dollar, or both.

USD::goods orders non defense ex air::m/.note: Nondefense Capital Goods Excluding Aircraft (often called core capital goods) measures new orders for business-investment goods in the Census M3/durable goods data. Stronger orders can support USD and often weigh on XAUUSD; weaker orders can support it.

USD::goods trade balance::none.note: BEA and Census report monthly trade in goods and services; the goods trade balance is goods exports minus goods imports.

USD::government payrolls::none.note: BLS Employment Situation (CES) reports the change in government payroll employment as part of total nonfarm payrolls. A stronger print can lift USD and yields and often pressure XAUUSD; a weaker print can support XAUUSD.

USD::heating oil stockpiles::none.note: EIA Weekly Petroleum Status Report includes distillate fuel oil inventories, commonly watched as heating oil stockpiles.

USD::house price index::m/m.note: FHFA House Price Index (HPI) measures changes in single-family home values.

USD::house price index::none.note: FHFA House Price Index (HPI) measures changes in single-family home values.

USD::house price index::y/y.note: FHFA House Price Index (HPI) measures changes in single-family home values.

USD::housing starts::m/m.note: Census New Residential Construction provides data on new privately-owned housing units started, under construction, and completed.

USD::housing starts::none.note: Census New Residential Construction provides national and regional counts of new privately-owned housing units started and completed.

USD::ibd/tipp economic optimism::none.note: IBD/TIPP Economic Optimism Index is a monthly sentiment survey of US consumers, with 50 as the neutral level (above 50 = net optimism). Stronger sentiment can lift USD and yields and often pressure XAUUSD; weaker sentiment can support XAUUSD.

USD::iea monthly report::none.note: IEA Oil Market Report (OMR) provides data, forecasts and analysis on the global oil market, including oil supply, demand, inventories, prices, refining activity, and oil trade.

USD::imf meetings::none.note: IMF and World Bank Annual and Spring Meetings bring together central bankers, ministers, and other leaders to discuss the global economic outlook and international development.

USD::import price index ex petroleum::m/.note: BLS US Import Price Index measures the change over time in prices of goods or services purchased from abroad by US residents, excluding petroleum.

USD::import price index::m/m.note: BLS US Import Price Index measures the change over time in prices of goods or services purchased from abroad by US residents.

USD::import price index::y/y.note: BLS US Import Price Index measures the change over time in prices of goods or services purchased from abroad by US residents.

USD::imports::none.note: BEA defines imports of goods and services as goods and services purchased by U.S. residents from foreign residents.

USD::industrial production::m/m.note: Industrial Production measures the month-over-month % change in industrial output. A higher-than-expected reading (vs forecast) can lift USD and yields, often pressuring XAUUSD; a weaker reading can support it.

ZAR::ppi::m/m.note: PPI (Producer Price Index, MoM) measures the month-over-month % change in prices received by producers.

ZAR::ppi::y/y.note: PPI (Producer Price Index, YoY) measures the year-over-year % change in prices received by producers.

ZAR::prime rate (2m)::none.note: South African prime lending rate (2m) is a quoted prime lending rate over a two-month tenor and typically moves with the SARB repo rate.

ZAR::prime rate::none.note: South African prime lending rate is the rate banks charge prime borrowers and typically moves with the SARB repo rate.

ZAR::private sector credit::none.note: Private Sector Credit measures credit or lending conditions.

ZAR::retail sales::y/y.note: Statistics South Africa retail sales (YoY) reports the year-over-year change in retail trade sales.

ZAR::s&p global manufacturing pmi::none.note: S&P Global South Africa Manufacturing PMI is a monthly survey-based diffusion index of manufacturing conditions (above 50 = expansion).

ZAR::sarb financial stability review::no.note: Sarb Financial Stability Review is a scheduled data release.

ZAR::sarb monetary policy review::none.note: Sarb Monetary Policy Review is a scheduled data release.

ZAR::sarb quarterly bulletin::none.note: Sarb Quarterly Bulletin is a scheduled data release.

ZAR::thomson reuters ipsos pcsi::m/m.note: Thomson Reuters/Ipsos PCSI is a survey-based consumer sentiment index for the country and this series is the monthly change.

ZAR::total vehicle sales::none.note: Total Vehicle Sales reports aggregate new vehicle sales reported by naamsa.

ZAR::total vehicle sales::y/y.note: Total Vehicle Sales shows the year-over-year change in aggregate new vehicle sales reported by naamsa.

ZAR::trade balance::none.note: South Africa trade balance reports the net balance of merchandise exports minus merchandise imports based on customs data.

ZAR::unemployment rate::none.note: Unemployment Rate shows the share of the labor force that is unemployed.

ZAR::unemployment::none.note: Unemployment is a scheduled data release.

ZMK::cpi::m/m.note: CPI (Consumer Price Index, MoM) measures the month-over-month % change in consumer prices.

ZMK::cpi::y/y.note: CPI (Consumer Price Index, YoY) measures the year-over-year % change in consumer prices.

ZMK::interest rate decision::none.note: Bank of Zambia sets its Policy Rate (Monetary Policy Rate) as the main signal of its monetary policy stance. Usually limited direct impact on XAUUSD unless it shifts broader yields or risk sentiment.

ZWL::cpi::m/m.note: CPI (Consumer Price Index, MoM) measures the month-over-month % change in consumer prices.

ZWL::cpi::y/y.note: CPI (Consumer Price Index, YoY) measures the year-over-year % change in consumer prices.
